Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: I saw it yesterday. It is not the greatest horror movie I have ever seen, but it is not as bad as people made it sound. My main criticism is that it is too much "over the top". Too many forest sounds, too many chases in the forest, the house is too decayed... What is great about found footage is that it is supposed to diffuse fright in a more subtle manner, rather than put you in panick mode for 90 minutes. We see too much of the witch, too much of the "ghosts". This movie just shows too much, and by doing so, lacks that charm the original had by suggesting all along (and in the end confirming) the presence of an unnatural force, rather than showing it in your face. It is overall well done though, it has a lot of effective jump scares, and is much intense and "fantastic" than the other. If it is what you like in a horror movie, you might like this one. I think it is worth seeing for every horror fan, so everyone can have his own opinion.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
I loved the way they combined body horror, claustrophobia and some scary shit strewn around. But the characters are a hit and miss.  there is no massive backstory(except for james), which is pretty good but his backstory is neither strong nor convincing enough (It becomes important in the climax)The first 30 mins are highly cliched, lots of false jumpscares, 'noises in the woods', partying,'the shit that starts off like nothing and then becomes a serious scary shit' and so on. Overall the story is drab, but they did stick to a recipe that can actually induce some scares.
Would rate 2.5/5. Worth a watch? If you have not seen a horror movie for a long time and want some entertainment for couple of hours, watch it. But please leave your logical thinkng behind and stop dissecting the movie if you want to enjoy it

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
Listen, I'm a huge fan of the first film. I've seen it easily about ten times in my life, and each time I enjoy it. The film was/is awesome because it created some kind of possibility that any one of us could rent a camera and shoot a movie dirt cheap, it gave people hope that anybody could make a movie. It's also very unsettling, much like the discomfort level you feel when watching The Texas Chainsaw Massacre (1974) because it almost felt like watching something really happen. TBWP is hosted as a last document, from start to finish, of three people's mysterious deaths. What more could you ask a horror movie to have?

It was also an original experience, a fresh idea and execution. 

Blair Witch, is not, as they claim, a "game changing" horror film. Blair Witch is a knock-off, a re-imagining. It's almost like Rob Zombie bought the rights to it and made it on his own (he didn't, obviously), in that same vein. The film, itself, contributed a few cool things for the mythos of the Blair Witch, few as in far and little. The rest of the movie, from start to finish, is basically completely derived from the first film. They took so many ideas that had already been thought up and stamped them in probably because it was easier than having the characters do something different with their time in the woods. 

They took an idea that could have had potential and turned it into another loud-bang thriller, one of many others, that rely on jump-scares way too much and doesn't tap any further than that.

Comment:
You can't make another film like The Blair Witch Project these days...  thanks to how niche this sub-genre of horror was, along its phenomenal marketing campaign, everyone thought it was real, that's what made it a memorable and popular film. But now if you watch it today, knowing it's fiction thanks to how mainstream the Internet has become in out lives, it just doesn't pull you in as much. It's not as liked now compared to when it first came out.
This new film should have just stuck with the title 'The Woods', and not 'Blair Witch', because now, people know what to expect out of this film.

Comment:
Damn, what's with all of these comments? I saw the movie tonight and it scared the shit out of me. Was so well made. I feel like everyone is just disregarding it because they're cult fans of the original or they're hopping on the bandwagon of "every new horror movie is shit". These movies are fun. Horror movies hardly ever have a deep, meaningful story. They are about scaring their audience, keeping them on the edge of their seat. This movie does it well. See it first at least, then formulate an opinion.

side note - This movie answers the question regarding why the dude in the original was standing in the corner facing the wall. They shouldn't have spoiled that part in the trailer IMO, look at the witch, you're dead.

Except for the last couple of seconds of the movie, this movie was actually pretty tense.
Especially the whole climax at the end. It was SO incredibly obvious who was going to die first, though. They didn't even try to get rid of that horrortrope :p
Furthermore I liked the characters. Thank the Gods they weren't douchebags or anything, but you still didn't got to know them in any kind of way, which was a shame. The Blair Witch really has some interesting powers she used against them.

Pff.. Pitoyable... Et vous y croyez vous que ça va faire peur?? La bande annonce est longue juste parce qu'ils ont essayé d'y caler les scènes les plus "terrifiantes" car ils se sont dit qu'on était pas dupe et qu'on allait penser que déjà faire un remake d'une légende de Blair Witch ça n'allait pas plaire dans le sens où les deux premiers volets étaient des légendes, mais en plus nous mettre une petite bande annonce ça serait encore plus pitoyable. Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
My opinion of the new Blair Witch movie: horrible. The whole thing was just completely full of tired cliches, the actors were pretty bad, the dialogue was not realistic, but the worst part was all the cheap jump scares...they weren't even GOOD jump scares. You literally saw nothing, ever. There would just suddenly be these loud bangs, the camera would jerk around wildly, and you would just see nothing at all. Just totally random loud bangs for no reason with sudden camera movement.

In my opinion, this movie represents and is a perfect example of a serious decline in America's intelligence and taste. Most of the people in the theater? They loved it. They actually loved this piece of shit excuse for a movie. I think in another couple of generations, this country is going to be so unbelievably stupid.

This movie doesn't hold a faint candle to the first, original Blair Witch Project.

The thing I hate most about this is that whether you like or hate the original Blaire Witch Project film, you must admit that it was its very own thing. It was the first of its kind. It literally created a new genre of horror movies. I personally adored the film with its looming feeling of terror and the idea of more "thinking of what's out there" than actually seeing it. 

And then when they do this to it. Adding jumpscares, gross out horror, meaningless gore, and even a cliche little girl voice singing a popular song slowly to make it seem scary, it's literally taking an original concept and shooting it in the throat. So, no. No thanks Hollywood.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
I honestly do not get the appeal of shoddy camera movies at all. 

The original Blair witch couldn't really tell its own story and left me thinking... that i didn't really see a film at all, and that i was supposed to believe it was real or something, at the least it feels like it wanted me to view it that way.

But people like it? it had a scene that was turned into a meme ten times over, placing the camera right under a girls nose as it starts running wasn't scary it was just cringy |:

This movie, objectively speaking, was just terrible. But it's getting a sequel because people liked it, meanwhile hordes of people hate on movies that are just fine.

Honestly the movie industry is getting pretty ridiculous, So many film series were destroyed before they even started despite being actually pretty good movies, for absolutely terrible reasons that are straight up nitpicking.

Yet a movie like this with amateur camera work that prevents us from seeing the character/s central to the plot in such a way that it's just annoying is actually successful? o_O

If you like it good for you, its an extra movie you can enjoy, and that isn't a bad thing.

I just honestly don't get how movies like this can be successful enough to generate a sequel, even if it's later down the line.

Yet movies such as john carter and Jupiter rising which are meant to be a film series, flop hard with pretty much no decent reason at all.

John carter's primary reason is that they deviated from the book somewhat, and it pissed off those who enjoyed the book. But for me, as someone who hadn't read the book, the movie itself was really good, and it would have been great for it to get its deserved sequel.

This is why people seem to think the films industry are running out of ideas. They aren't, the creative stuff just seems to flop for dumb reasons |:

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: It goes to show the difference in generations. What made the first Blair witch good, was how understated it was.  It didn't rely on loud noises and jump-scares to be scary.  It was done in such a way that it put the viewer in the experience, too.  The movie was emotional and scary because you could empathize with the characters, and suspend your disbelief to a point where you felt like you were there.  Nowadays, most horror movies rely on shaky-cam and predictable jump-scares, in lieu of a good story or suspenseful plot lines or emotional character arcs.  The first Blair witch was somewhat believable because it left the supernatural elements to your imagination, whereas (albeit all of my info is only from the trailer) this new one looks to be more "in your face" with it.  It's like they focus-grouped the first movie, and just took all the scary parts that tested well from the first one and just made a movie about those parts.  Obviously I haven't seen the movie yet, but as is the case with mostly all modern horror movies, it's probably overdone and not truly going to live up to the reviews and claims of it being "One of the scariest movies ever made". Attention spans have shortened these days. If you take a teenager and try to get them to watch the original "Psycho", or "The Exorcist", they would probably tell you that it's too slow and not scary.  To me, a scary movie comes from the plot, not the special effects.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: When the original was released, I was buried in a mixture of school studies, drunken parties and getting high(college years). My older sister told me all about this movie that was found and was an unsolved video clips that was edited into a documentary. We went on the first day. Back then you couldn't google if it was fake or get IMDb info on your mobile. Basically we went into this thing thinking it was real, and so was the rest of the theater. I've never been so scared/concerned in my life. When the movie ended you could hear a pin drop.  It was also hot as hell in the theater. I always wondered if they purposely asked theaters to turn off the AC during the movie. I also remember how swarms of people were chatting afterwards about what we had just watched. When have you ever done that with the movie? Initially I was bummed that it was fake but I love that I got to experience what the director had intended for the first couple of days.

The fact so much is left to the viewer's imagination is what's so effective, as well as the low budget. The protagonists didn't have the greatest equipment they could. The stuff they'll be using in this movie is too good to be believable. The biggest thing is that I fear they may go and do something stupid and show us what's chasing them. We never saw the Blair Witch or God knows whatever else may have been after the college students in the first movie and that worked so damn well. I never found something for me to interpret so horrifying in my life. If we see the Blair Witch, it's going to fail to hold up to the unseen one from the first movie for obvious reasons. This movie is doomed.

Just a well thought out, intriguing, and truly terrifying film would be nice. Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
What made the first one so charming and memorable was the fact that the cast was being fucked with half the time, if not ALL the time. The people they interviewed at the beginning of the film were all actors (unbeknownst to them), and whenever they were camping out or wandering through the woods, members from the cast would go off and do some creepy shit to freak them out. Their reactions of terror and anxiety were genuine, and the fact that the movie was shot on a tiny budget of $60,000 was paramount in ensuring its box office success.

Not to mention, it was an original concept that hadn't really been done before in the West (please correct me if I'm mistaken on this). The fact that we're just hearing about this movie now is just fucking sad and is clearly an attempt on the part of the filmmakers to cash in on a franchise that's been all but forgotten about.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: They fucking forgot what made the first Blair Witch great, which was subtlety. The unnerving feeling you had because you didn't know what the fuck was happening. Your mind made most of the scary shit up and that's what the movie set out to do. It was successful in making you feel scared without showing you much of anything, letting your imagination do the work while engrossing you in the lore and atmosphere little by little, which made the ending as jarring as it was. Hell, in the end, you never saw much of anything, and that's fucking great. Now this pile of garbage on a hot summer day reveals every cliche in the handy cam book while giving away the whole movie in the goddamn trailer, letting you know it's throwing out everything you liked about subtlety and giving you everything you hate about modern horror. Guarantee you're gonna see the Blair Witch. I fucking guarantee it, on my Men's Warehouse shit, I fucking guarantee they will add ghost children, maybe zombies, possession, demons, the whole 9 yards. Everything except quality.

Comment:
Hardly original. 
Found footage movies are mostly terrible because they are an excuse for lazy camera work (swinging a camera around and using profanity for an hour doesn't make a good movie). 

I found Paranormal Activity 2, Marble Hornets, and V/H/S to be competent horror movies in the "found footage" genre. But I've seen about a hundred that are just repeats of half-baked ideas. Oooh, I have a camera and access to an abandoned building...I'm going to waste everyone's time.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
What the original Blair Witch had that this new one will not and never have:

1. Shitty camera to enhance the realism of an amateur filmmaker.
2. No music, no editing, just pure ambience of the forest, which was more scary than some shitty stock horror music.
3. Likeable characters.
4. On the spot amateur acting.
5. Loosely based/no script at all.
6. No safety net of an actual camera crew to guide them in the forest.
7. Memorable scenes.
8. Innovative theme that made a landmark in the horror genre.
9. Left a terror that wasn't a jumpscare but an ill feeling that made you go the fuck to sleep at night so the Blair Witch wouldn't get you. 
10. Great, natural pacing.
11. Ending that didn't necessarily leave you in shock but to wonder What The Fuck Happened.

If I left anything out feel free to add onto it.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
Many say Hollywood doesn't have original ideas anymore, hence the remake. Not true. There are a gazillion scripts out there from unknowns, but Hollywood is a "closed shop", and it's all about money, not art. Since studios already own the rights for a film, it's cheaper for them to create a remake. The hope is that since the formula worked before, it will work again for a new audience. It's about return on investment, nothing more.

If you want Hollywood to stop its remaking juggernaut, don't see any remakes in theaters. Otherwise, unless the US economy bounces back on a grand scale, seeing new and original commercial films from Los Angeles will be few and far between.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
The greatest difference between these two movies, is that the first one was "found footage" which a lot of us believed.. That is what made that movie scary. Because it was supposedly FOUND and REAL footage; there was no music, no jump scares, just children's voices, the sounds of the woods at night and cryptic messages they would find and dead body parts. Watching that movie and believing it was all found footage is was scared the shit out if me. This new movie is not based on. Found footage; it's us watching what happened to his sister and her friends. Don't you want to know? I always wanted to know..I seen the original in the movie theater and the ending terrified me and I cried for that guy standing in the corner and we speculated what had happened to him.. I thought the whole thing was real.. Yes, I was gullible,  but I'm guessing I wasn't alone in that. But the point is, we were left wondering what happened to her..  And I'm
Hoping we get to find that out.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: I know this is said often, but I'm not sure that this one is going to stack up all that well to the original.... and that's kind of a good thing. The directors of the first Blair Witch were kinda terrible human beings. All that anger and anxiety and terror that you see from the actors in the movie is real. The directors gave the actors their script and camera, and then gave them them the shooting locations, which also had food. As the filming went on, though, the amount of food the actors were given began to shrink. Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: Blair Witch 99 first came out online, pictures and stories were written about people going missing trying to discover the "Blair Witch". Three people auditioned to be part of a film and were dropped in the middle of bush, were told an outline of a story, given a camera and improvised the rest. The directors would make the little figures out of sticks, threw away a map and even took a cast member away, the rest were up to the talents of the actors to react to these consequences. The story on the website got out and people wanted to see this documentary style movie most believing this was all true. Thats why it was a great film, experimental director's, concept, actors and ideas made this movie. I just hope the 16' edition doesnt fuck with that for $$

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: I was 21 when the "Blair Witch Project" came out, and I went with a group of friends to see it in the theater. Everyone was horrified. It was a completely new twist in the whole horror genre with the "found footage" concept. Being a part of that was something I will never forget. It was genuinely frightening. No gorey slasher scenes, no CGI, no big Hollywood budget, just a few relatable kids with a video camera, and the terror of what lurked in the shadows stalking them. Unfortunately these days, no one is really scared of anything anymore. Jump scares are expected in "horror" movies, and it's always the same predictable principle. I am curious about this new movie. But nothing will ever chill me to the bone the way the "Blair Witch Project" did in the 1990's.

Comment: Not sure how well this will do.  Obviously being that the concept has already been had, any subsequent movie simply cannot be as good do to familiarity.  The original Blair Witch movie I thought was completely cool!  It was a new concept in film making, and once you got the story, made for a great experience. I will definitely spend the money to see this at the theater.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: A proper sequel where it's Heather Donahue's brother obsessed with the found footage film and he goes to find the answers to his sister's unresolved dissapearance. This is exactly how I would have imagined the sequel except it would have been found footage too. The original was so visceral and realistic. You couldn't even tell they were acting at all. They looked genuinely terrified and confused and angry. Yes you didn't see what killed them but you'd be utterly terrified if you put yourself in their situation. Seeing ritualistic crosses made out of sticks hung around you, hearing children at night, having your tent being broke into by an unseen force, going in circles no matter what direction you walk, and finding your friends teeth and tongue in a shirt when he goes missing after taking a piss. Realistic, terrifying situations to be in. Nothing will ever top it.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
Yeah this will work great. The good thing about the first one was there was a reality to it. The actors actually did get lost. One of them dropped a $10,000 camera. Everyone was cold and tired and didn't sleep and they started hating each other. The internet wasn't as big back then so people (I was in high school at the time) actually thought this was a real event and not a movie. It was the first "found footage" movie that really made the genre (The Last Broadcast came first but it was pretty shit) and it played with horror tropes spectacularly. If you thought "it was boring" you're probably too young or retarded to understand horror and I *guarantee* you thought Insidious was a good movie.

Making a sequel in 2016 with HD camera, obvious actors, the internet and everything... it's not going to work. I can tell by the trailer alone that it's not going to work because they're going to show everything and fucking ruin the pacing.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: Lionsgate: This trailer just seems by the numbers horror trailer. Pounding incidental music and quick cuts and some heavy handed attempts of imagery from the first film (totems, handprints and a person standing in the corner) and the " I am so sorry "quote . The original film had just ambient sound  and was cinema verite and was a slow burn that I personally enjoyed and the soundtrack; Josh's Blair Witch Mix was awesome. It wont take much effort to be a improvement over book of shadows but, you did have a return on your investment so that's a check in the plus column. I going to wait for the next trailer to see if you will be getting  my money.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment:
Remember back when this movie was titled The Woods, and how the trailers revealed so little about the plot like any good trailer should, and how the movie felt like it had potential to not only tell an original story, but be scary as hell? Yeah, well all that hope is gone now. What the fuck. And now this trailer is garbage. And now the movie it's advertising looks like garbage. I may not have liked The Blair Witch Project, but at least it had an original idea, and its impact was undeniable. I thought that The Woods could have been an incredible movie, but instead it turned into a sequel to The Blair Witch Project. Fuck you, Hollywood. Fuck you. Fuck you for luring me in with the promise of a good movie, then shitting in my hand. I am literally angry.

But hey, if this turns out to be good, then I will stand corrected. But as of now, this movie looks like every other found footage horror movie ever, complete with an unoriginal idea and a litany of deafeningly loud jumpscares.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: The reason the first one was scary was because it was the fear of the unknown. It hinted at the fact that there was something paranormal but it could have easily just been some teens trying to fuck with them, or some murderer, or ANYTHING. The movie hinted at so many possibilities at the beginning, with the creepy lady with a fence made out of twigs (like the stick men in the trees) and the two fishermen who knew a lot about the Blair witch, where it could have been any number of things that could have happened to them, not just something paranormal. This fucking movie not only is an attempt to bank off the original, but ruins what made the original scary, and takes away whatever people wanted to believe. Everyone is scared of the unknown, but paranormal shit is so fucking over played now a days. If you liked the original Blair witch or not, it fucking changed horror films forever. We don't need "Paranormal Activity: Woods". This is such bullshit.

Comment: Okay, THIS is more like it. I personally couldn't get into the first one because there was no indication of presence from anything in the film, no footsteps, no wind, not even an eerie hum or ear ringing noise to indicate the floating witch from the original design. Here we actually hear things other than a few children giggles and see vague glimpses of something. some indication of presence. I get the first film had the budget of a sandwitch (wah wah), but even with that budget, SOME sort of effect could've done something. It always felt like they were alone and felt less real due to the constant insistence on using the camera the way they did, made it less scary for me. Here they use go pro  and cellphone style cameras and actually DROP THEM when they run. Although it looks a little jumpscarefest-y, so trust is still not %100.

Title: Blair Witch (2016 Movie) - Official Trailer
Comment: A bit of trivia, if you don't wanna do your own research. At the end of this trailer there's a little snippet of a song sung creepily by a woman. That song was actually the trailer song for "The Woods" which is actually what this film's original title was supposed to be. I guess for a marketing push the true name of "Blair Witch" was kept from audiences in favor of a more generic horror title to build intrigue on the film. Shows what a little misdirection can do for people. Sorry for the super long trivia fact I just thought I'd share it if no one wanted to do research.
